nd ioctl() implementations are/were particularly nasty in<br />&gt; this respect.  So many of them were doing checks against the current thread,<br />&gt; not f_cred.<br /><br />So ioctl() may be ok, simply because at least you shouldn't be able to<br />fool suid programs to do ioctl's on untrusted file descriptors.<br /><br />So using current_cred() is still technically very wrong, but it's<br />probably not a huge problem in practice.<br /><br />Now, if there's some cachefs kind of "do ioctl at the behest of<br />somebody else", then *that* would be a problem. I'm hoping there<br />isn't.<br /><br />               Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
